<h1>Things to See</h1>
<h2>
  Lower Connecticut
</h2>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.stamfordct.gov/city-parks/pages/cove-island-park">Cove Island Park</a></span>
    (1125 Cove Rd. Stamford, CT): Cove Island is a favorite spot for families, joggers, and dog walkers thanks to its one-mile paved trail, playground, and beach. Right on the coastline, it offers views of Long Island across the Sound and is a great place for an easy walk.
  </p>
  <p>
  <span class="location-name">Downtown New Canaan</span>
    (198 Elm St. New Canaan, CT): With a number of restaurants, boutiques, an antique shop or two, and an independent bookstore, New Canaan is a great town to wander around for a couple of hours.
  </p>
  <p>
  <span class="location-name"><a href="http://greenwich.audubon.org/">Greenwich Audubon</a></span>
    (613 Riversville Rd. Greenwich, CT): A nice hiking and birding spot with 7 miles of trails that wind through several different types of habitats.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://stamfordmuseum.org/">Stamford Museum &amp; Nature Center</a></span> (39 Scofieldtown Rd. Stamford, CT): The Stamford Nature Center features a farm, a small museum with rotating exhibits, and trails covering over 80 acres (including an accessible nature trail) that also interlink with the neighboring Bartlett Arboretum.
  </p>
  <p>
  <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.sterlingfarmsgc.com/">Sterling Farms Golf Course</a></span>
    (1349 NewField Ave. Stamford, CT): Elizabeth’s home golf course, Sterling is a nicely kept, 18-hole public course with a fair, fun set-up. Don’t have time to play a full round? There’s also a covered driving range open rain or shine!
  </p>
<h2>
  Lower and Middle Hudson Valley
</h2>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.diaart.org/visit/visit/diabeacon-beacon-united-states">Dia Beacon</a></span>
    (3 Beekman St. Beacon, NY): This modern art installation features an impressive array of large sculptures and paintings. If twisted metal, broken glass, dramatic scale, and experimental abstract art sound like your cup of tea, this is a neat place to spend a few hours. Coffee and gift shops on-site.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.hudsonvalley.org/historic-sites/kykuit">Kykuit</a></span>
    (381 N Broadway, Sleepy Hollow, NY): A variety of tours of the stone mansion, built by the Rockefeller family in the early 20th century, are offered (reservations recommended). In addition to the house itself, Kykuit is home to extensive grounds/gardens, a 20th century sculpture collection, art galleries, and an automobile/carriage collection.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.lyndhurst.org/">Lyndhurst</a></span>
    (635 S Broadway, Sleepy Hollow, NY): An early Gothic Revival mansion, Lyndhurst was built in the first half of the 19th century and houses a collection of art, antiques, and other period furnishings. Several different guided tours of the house and ground are offered; reservations recommended.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.hudsonvalley.org/historic-sites/philipsburg-manor">Philipsburg Manor</a></span>
    (381 N Broadway, Sleepy Hollow, NY): This 18th century farm, grist mill, and trading center was owned by a family of Anglo-Dutch merchants and was also home to European tenant farmers and African slaves. Guided tours include a visit to the manor home, the mill, the barn, and hands-on farming activities.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://stonebarnscenter.org/">Stone Barns Center for Food and Agriculture</a></span>
    (630 Bedford Rd. Pocantico Hills, NY): In addition to being the site of our wedding, Blue Hill is a fully working farm and center for food and agriculture that hosts daily tours and activities. If you’re interested in touring the farm, please note that reservations are recommended.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://stormking.org/">Storm King Art Center</a></span>
    (1 Museum Rd. New Windsor, NY): Similar to Dia Beacon in terms of artistic style, but a better bet if you prefer outdoor art. This expansive property is beautiful and features massive outdoor sculptures and a dramatic landscape that is excellent for a long walk. Sneakers or other sturdy walking shoes recommended.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.vassar.edu/">Vassar College</a></span>
    (124 Raymond Ave. Poughkeepsie, NY): It’s a bit of a drive, but we couldn’t resist throwing this on here. In addition to being a wonderful liberal arts college, Vassar boasts an absolutely beautiful campus that also happens to be an arboretum. If you’re looking to catch lunch in the area as part of your visit, definitely consider stopping at Babycakes Cafe, a favorite spot of ours from our college days!
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://parks.westchestergov.com/ward-pound-ridge-reservation">Ward Pound Ridge Reservation</a></span>
    (6 Reservation Rd. Pound Ridge, NY): The Pound Ridge Reservation is one of our favorite places to hike in the lower Connecticut/lower Hudson Valley area. The reservation is over 4,000 acres and includes an extensive network of well-blazed trails. Hiking boots and a trail map are strongly recommended!
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.hudsonvalley.org/historic-sites/washington-irvings-sunnyside">Washington Irving’s Sunnyside</a></span>
    (3 W Sunnyside Ln, Tarrytown, NY): The home of the Washington Irving, best known for his short stories (“The Legend of Sleepy Hollow” and “Rip Van Winkle”), Sunnyside is a national historic landmark that was built in the first half of the 19th century. Guided tours of the home and grounds are offered.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.simon.com/mall/the-westchester">Westchester Mall</a></span>
    (125 Westchester Ave. White Plains, NY): Forget your tie? Inclement weather (we hope not!)? The Westchester Mall is a great spot to do some serious shopping.
  </p>
<h2>
  New York City (and Boroughs)
</h2>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.amnh.org/">American Museum of Natural History</a></span>
    (Central Park West @ 79th St. New York, NY): Home to extensive permanent collections on flora, fauna, astronomy, earth science, fossils (the dinosaur halls are a must see!), human origins, human culture, and a number of special exhibits, the Museum of Natural History is worth a full-day visit.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://bronxzoo.com/">Bronx Zoo</a></span>
    (2300 Southern Blvd. Bronx, NY): The Bronx Zoo is truly world class--even on a cloudy and/or chilly day, it is definitely worth a visit! The Zoo is home to over 650 species of animals (be sure not to miss the World of Birds!) and features an extensive network of walking paths.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.metmuseum.org/visit/met-cloisters">The Cloisters</a></span>
    (99 Margaret Corbin Dr. New York, NY): The Cloisters is home to the MET’s collection of Medieval European art and serves as a peaceful oasis from the city thanks to its monastery-inspired layout.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.metmuseum.org/">The Metropolitan Museum of Art</a></span>
    (1000 Fifth Ave. New York, NY): A world-class art museum with extensive permanent collections and special exhibits spanning thousands of years, there’s something for everyone at the MET. Highlights (for us) include the Ancient Egyptian, Ancient Greek and Roman collections.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="location-name"><a href="http://www.nybg.org/home/">New York Botanical Gardens</a></span>
    (2900 Southern Blvd. Bronx, NY): The Botanical Gardens cover 250 acres and supports over a million plants from around the world.
  </p>
